<TEXT>
the government has begun a study of a rare cattle 
disease that has worried the domestic industry and prompted two 
countries to ban british livestock officials said 
the disease has not been documented in any other country though 
there have been anecdotal reports from the united states said dr 
james hope head of an independent research unit studying the 
disease 
hope said 833 cases of the disease which affects the animals 
central nervous system were discovered since 1986 among 13 million 
british dairy cows it is more common in sheep 
the government has launched an inquiry into the disease known 
as bovine spongiform encephalopachy officials said thursday they 
said there was at present no evidence humans could catch it by 
eating beef 
israel and australia have banned imports of british cattle 
according to an official for the ministry of agriculture fisheries 
and food who spoke on condition of anonymity 
</TEXT>
