<TEXT>
a former top navy contracting official says 
that as a private consultant he paid other consultants for 
technical information on contracts but denies he paid 
government employees 
william parkin who is at the center of the ongoing pentagon 
fraud investigation said he began making monthly payments to 
consultant fred lackner in late 1986 for information on a pending 
navy contract for special aircraft equipment 
parkin who retired from the navy in 1983 to set up his own 
consulting firm said he paid lackner between 15000 and 18000 
and that he then provided the contract information to his client 
hazeltine corp of greeenlawn ny on long island 
i will say it wasnt secret material parkin said in a 
telephone interview friday with the associated press it was 
technical information 
a hazeltine official speaking for the company on condition of 
anonymity said hazeltine had been assured by investigators that 
neither it nor any current or former employee is a target of the 
investigation and has no knowledge of parkin acquiring any 
information unlawfully 
hazeltine was aware that parkin worked with other consultants 
but was not generally aware of the identity of those consultants 
the official continued and specifically hazeltine was not aware 
that fred lackner was one of them lackner has never worked as a 
consultant to hazeltine 
the official said there was a standard clause in parkins 
contract with hazeltine obligating him not to obtain inside 
information by bribery 
the justice department has asserted in an affidavit for a search 
warrant that wiretapped conversations showed parkin served as a 
middleman who paid government employees for inside information and 
sold it to contractors 
i deny vehemently that i made payoffs to government 
officials parkin was quoted as telling the wall street journal 
in an article published friday i bought information from 
consultant lackner and passed it to hazeltine that is where i 
made an error 
parkin is the second consultant this week to describe an 
informal and extensive network of consultants government officials 
and defense contractors whose interests in passing information 
often meshed 
thomas muldoon another consultant who like parkin was named 
in federal search warrants in june was quoted by the hartford 
courant in connecticut on sunday as saying he never asked about the 
sources of sensitive information he received from other consultants 
and neither did the companies to which he passed it 
companies never ask you where you get the information 
muldoon said there was never any doubt what i was being paid 
for 
parkin 64 of alexandria va first described his work as a 
middleman in the defense industry during a series of interviews 
with the journal which described him as one of the navys most 
powerful contracting officers from 1966 to 1983 
parkin was hired by hazeltine in 1986 to help win navy work on 
test equipment for systems that distinguish between friendly and 
hostile aircraft he was paid about 36000 by the company over a 
1year period 
parkin told the journal his role was only to serve as a 
front for lackner now a california defense consultant who also 
was the object of an fbi search warrant earlier this summer 
parkin said lackner obtained the confidential information and 
that he then passed it on without lackner ever disclosing how he 
got it 
the information tells ahead of time what would be in the 
request for proposals advance information so they hazeltine 
could start a proposal parkin said 
lackner was quoted by the journal as saying the information he 
gave parkin was not inside information he also told the paper he 
had obtained information in the past from stuart berlin currently 
a navy executive and another figure in the investigation but said 
it was public knowledge 
parkin also disclosed a lengthy list of dealings with various 
consultants and others who now figure in the procurement fraud 
investigation 
among those dealings were loans to an air force official whose 
office was searched by the fbi and joint investments with william 
galvin a defense consultant identified as a key figure in the 
probe 
the justice department investigation which became public in 
june centers on allegations that defense contractors routinely 
used outside consultants to obtain proprietary information on the 
bids of competitors and that the consultants may have paid bribes 
to pentagon employees 
</TEXT>
