<TEXT>
swaying in rhythm with a lineup of rock stars 
tens of thousands packed wembley stadium on friday for a concert 
that kicks off a global tour launched by amnesty international in 
the cause of human rights 
bruce springsteen peter gabriel sting and others opened the 
sixhour concert with a rendition of get up stand up by the 
late reggae singer bob marley 
rain cleared shortly before the start of the concert and the 
stars began belting out their songs from a podium surrounded by a 
blue and green map of the world embossed with universal 
declaration of human rights in red letters 
the concert at the 100000capacity stadium begins a sixweek 
world tour which hopes to reach 20 cities on five continents to 
mark the 40th anniversary of the human rights declaration by the 
united nations 
amnesty international which monitors human rights worldwide and 
won the 1977 nobel peace prize launched the 23 million 
extravaganza to stir the consciences of the young 
the goodnatured crowd packing the arena below the artists 
raised their arms to send human waves rippling around the stadium 
springsteen is sharing the bill for the entire tour with british 
stars gabriel and sting american tracey chapman and senegals 
youssou ndour 
the stadium exploded in applause as springsteen the last artist 
to perform solo led off with born in the usa thousands of 
british youngsters rose in the grandstands and joined in 
the finale with all the performers joining in was chimes of 
freedom 
the rolling concert with its 200 participants traveling in five 
trucks and a chartered jet moves to paris on sunday after one 
night at wembley and then to budapest sept 6 
the venues include african and latin american nations that have 
been sensitive to amnestys accusations against them 
jack healey head of the us division of amnesty international 
said the concert was still negotiating for a date in moscow 
i am hopeful that negotiations dont break down on our side or 
on theirs healey said we are very anxious to play in the 
other superpower 
among the more contentious negotiations was a date in harare 
capital of zimbabwe whose government reacted angrily to amnesty 
reports several years ago of brutal suppression of the minority 
ndebele tribe the organizers announced friday that the date was 
fixed at oct 7 after what healey called a careful negotiation 
other confirmed venues are turin italy on sept 8 barcelona 
spain sept 10 san jose costa rica on sept 13 toronto and 
montreal in canada on sept 1617 philadelphia on sept 19 los 
angeles on sept 21 tokyo sept 27 new delhi on sept 30 sao 
paulo brazil on oct 12 mendoza argentina on oct 14 and 
buenos aires the argentine capital for a grand finale on oct 15 
signatories to the un declaration range from democracies to 
dictatorships and include many of the countries who are accused by 
amnesty international of human rights abuses such as political 
murder torture and racial persecution 
more than a million people are expected to see the concerts 
live and the organizers estimate tv audiences may eventually reach 
1 billion 
amnesty international stressed the tour aimed to raise 
consciousness not money 
this tour is not about charity its about justice healey 
said 
he said he couldnt be more pleased with the turnout at the 
wembley concert hundreds of young people took time out to sign 
endorsements of the human rights declaration on leaflets 
springsteen said before the start of the concert that at 38 he 
no longer believed he could pick up a guitar and change the 
world 
but i do believe you can save a life someone comes to the 
show they hear the message they write a letter and someone 
gets out of prison early thats pretty good 
ticket prices vary according to national per capita incomes 
3760 in london but only 3 in budapest 
this is definitely not for fundraising said healey who 
put together a twoweek american tour called conspiracy of hope 
in 1986 featuring gabriel sting and the irish group u2 
us membership rose by 100000 to 250000 in the following 
year amnesty internationals worldwide membership is 750000 
every audience member will get a card with the text of the un 
declaration on human rights spectators will also be able to sign 
slips of paper saying they uphold the declaration at the end of 
the tour amnesty plans to deliver these to the governments of the 
countries visited 
