<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880903-0016 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the crew of downed delta flight 1141 
called out that the jets wing flaps were in the proper position 
for takeoff according to cockpit recordings released friday 
adding more confusion to the crash investigation 
national transportation safety board member lee dickinson said 
at a briefing friday night that the statements captured by the 
flight recorder seem to disagree with physical evidence found at 
the scene of wednesdays accident in which 13 people died 
dickinson said the recording clearly indicates someone making a 
pretakeoff call out for flaps and someone responding 15 15 
green light he said that would seem to indicate both flaps were 
shown to be in a matching angle of 15 degrees downward a normal 
takeoff position for a boeing 727 
flight engineer steven judd also told the ntsb team friday that 
he also heard the crews first officer say 15 15 
flaps help provide the lift a plane needs to become airborne 
the delta jetliner crashed as it tried to take off from dallasfort 
worth international airport 
investigators said the flaps in the wreckage appeared to be in 
the up position and the airplanes slats on the wings leading 
edge were found to be partly extended the boeing 727s slats have 
physical locking devices that would have prevented them from 
being knocked far out of place by a crash said bernard loeb 
deputy director of investigations for the ntsb 
officials said they have not determined which voices belong to 
the specific crew members 
another inconsistency investigators noted was no visible sign of 
damage to any of the planes three engines dickinson said they 
will have to wait until the pratt amp whitney power plants are torn 
down at the factory in hartford conn to learn more 
judd told investigators all three engines appeared to be 
operating normally up until the time the nose wheel was lifting off 
8500 to 9000 feet down runway 18l 
judd also said the right wing dipped severely after takeoff 
and capt larry davis tried to correct the situation 
the flight engineer said the plane had a very long wait for 
takeoff and for a time shut down the right engine which was 
separated from the fuselage after the crash 
witness accounts that the engines flared during takeoff could 
indicate compressor stall a phenomenon in which air flow to a 
jet engines compressor is interrupted loeb said but he said such 
a condition could not be confirmed yet 
loeb said he would not care to speculate on what position into 
which a pilot would have to move his flaps if the planes nose 
attitude was too extreme as some witnesses told the ntsb earlier 
the federal officials said they would continue to study the left 
rear emergency door near where many of the victims were found 
loeb said it took more than one person to open the door for the 
first time after the crash but he cautioned that no conclusion 
could be drawn that people may have been trapped inside by a 
troublesome door the angle of the wreckage combined with 
gravitational forces may have made the door difficult to open he 
said 
ninetyfive of the 108 people on board survived most by 
scrambling out of emergency doors over the left wing and a crack 
between the cabin and cockpit of the jet which broke apart and 
burst into flames as it plowed into a field of sunflowers at the 
end of the runway 
investigators thursday discovered an indicator of wing flap 
position was stuck in a position not normal for most takeoffsthey 
found the indicator in the up position opposite of the proper 
setting for takeoff but stressed it could have been jarred during 
the crash or by crew members during evacuation 
the cockpit recording also showed that the shaker stick 
which rattles a planes steering mechanism when a problem develops 
sounded during takeoff investigators said 
the recording also indicated that the crew in the cockpit 
discussed a possible engine problem during the few seconds of the 
flight and pilots in planes waiting on taxiways when flight 1141 
took off reported seeing a white flame or vapor from the planes 
left engine 
friday a forklift picked up the planes right engine which was 
found separated from the fuselage after the crash and placed it on 
a large flatbed truck where it was secured with chains for 
shipment to pratt amp whitney 
the boeing 727 is designed to fly even if one of its three 
engines is out officials have said 
investigators hope the fact that the flights cockpit crew 
survived will help them more easily reconstruct the accident 
the pilot capt larry l davis 48 was in fair condition 
friday at parkland memorial hospital while 1st officer carey 
wilson kirkland jr 37 was in stable condition at northeast 
community hospital at bedford 
john mazor a spokesman for the air line pilots association 
said davis should not be interviewed until he has recovered more 
and is no longer under the influence of painkillers 
what you dont do is take someone out of a smoldering cockpit 
and shove a tape recorder under their nose mazor said the 
account you get is going to be unreliable 
dickinson said blood and urine samples had been taken from the 
crew members shortly after they arrived hospitals wednesday would 
be tested for traces of drugs and alcohol such tests are routine 
after accidents 
as investigators continued studying the wreckage friday more 
attention was placed on the closed emergency exit on the left side 
of the plane toward the back near the galley 
tarrant county medical examiner nizan peerwani said the bodies 
of seven passengers and two flight attendants were found 
literally piled on top of one another in front of an exit door 
that apparently could not be opened 
federal safety investigators and delta officials declined to 
speculate on whether the unopened exit was a factor in the deaths 
but dickinson said ntsb personnel are trying to determine whether 
the door was jammed other exits are also being studied 
bill berry an atlantabased delta spokesman declined to 
speculate on why the victims were unable to open the exit 
ordinarily he said a door on a 727 can be opened manually in 
about two seconds 
the plane carried nearly a score of offduty delta employees 10 
of them flight attendants some passengers said their presence 
contributed to the miraculous number of survivors 
several passengers credited damon berry 37 of sandy utah an 
offduty delta employee on the flight with staying in the burning 
plane to help others 
i cant really say what was going through my mind he said 
you just do it it just seemed like my responsibility to try and 
help as many people as i could 
