four defiant yonkers city councilmen held fast 
to their refusal to bargain with a federal judge sending their 
troubled city toward bankruptcy for continuing to resist a 
courtordered desegregation plan 
one day after he was given a green light by the us supreme 
court us district judge leonard sand on friday reimposed fines 
on the city just north of new york that can soon amount to 1 
million a day and bankrupt it in short order 
the judge then unsuccessfully tried to work out a settlement in 
informal talks with the recalcitrant councilmen but the discussion 
ended within an hour with the two sides apparently no closer to 
agreement 
in 1985 sand found the city guilty of racially segregating 
housing for four decades the city council has refused to approve 
plans to build low and moderateincome housing to aid 
desegregation 
the nations highest court thursday night affirmed the crippling 
levy sand imposed in his effort to bring the city into line with 
the law 
however the court stayed the 500aday personal fines and jail 
terms sand had imposed on the four councilmen 
sand said that despite the stay the councilmen still have a 
responsibility to the citizens they represent who will bear the 
brunt of these city fines 
sand ordered the city to pay the fines accumulated over the 
labor day weekend 192000 on tuesday as previously promised 
by sand more than 85000 of the money will be earmarked for 
yonkers public schools and to guarantee the payment of interest on 
city bonds the balance will go to the us treasury and is 
nonrefundable 
sand then called on lawyers for all parties in the 
longsimmering legal battle to meet with him privately to explore 
informally some ideas we have for a possible solution of this 
crisis 
lawyers for both sides and city officials emerged tightlipped 
from the brief meeting in the new york courtroom 
