europes largest aviation event the farnborough 
air show opens sunday in southern england with daredevil 
aerobatics scheduled to go ahead despite the air show disaster in 
west germany 
if anything the interest is greater said air commodore dan 
honley spokesman for the organizers of the weeklong show at 
farnborough 35 miles southwest of london 
of course we are proud of the fact that our air displays are 
the safest in the world weve been refining the rules for almost 
40 years honley said in an interview 
the british red arrows the royal air forces display team of 
seven scarlet hawk fighters regularly thrill crowds at air shows 
in britain and abroad they are to perform daily wednesday through 
next sunday to a show that organizers say will attract about 
350000 visitors 
but at farnborough among the worlds biggest showcases of new 
civil and military aircraft air displays are a sideline to the 
serious business of selling 
this year 700 aerospace manufacturers from 24 countries 
including the united states and the soviet union are showing their 
wares the organizers say sales could top 167 billion worth of 
orders made during the last farnborough show 
for the first time soviet fighters are on display in the west 
two mig29s the soviet unions newest and most advanced 
warplanes flew into farnborough last week with a welcoming escort 
of royal air force tornado fighters they will go through their 
paces daily flying low over the hampshire countryside 
also at farnborough will be the latest versions of the us f16 
and f18 fighterbombers and making its air show debut the us 
marine corps harrier 2 
on the civil side mcdonnell douglas is unveiling its md80 
engine whose representatives claim can save up to 40 percent in 
fuel consumption 
the aerospace industry is booming and the air transport 
industry is booming said honley deputy director of the 
sponsoring society of british aerospace companies 
he predicted record orders for farnborough which alternates 
with le bourget in paris as host of the annual show 
farnborough opens under the shadow of last sundays disaster at 
the ramstein us air force base when three aircraft of the italian 
tricolored arrows display team collided during a complex air 
manuever 
one of the aircraft crashed into the crowd and exploded 
fiftyone people were killed at least 170 are hospitalized and 15 
remain unaccounted for 
after the ramstein disaster west germany suspended all air 
displays amid growing calls for a permanent ban throughout the nato 
western alliance 
honley said the red arrows operate under stringent safety rules 
and are not permitted to perform directly over spectators or fly 
toward them the most hairraising manuevers when planes zoom 
toward each other from opposite directions and then peel off are 
restricted to two aircraft 
theyd never be allowed to do the sort of manuever that the 
italians did honley said wed never have five aircraft flying 
one way four the other and yet a third at a right angle to both 
and that aircraft flying toward the crowds in our opinion that is 
diabolical 
farnborough where pilots have to fly their displays in front of 
a committee of experts before the show starts has not had an 
accident involving spectators since 1952 when a de haviland jet 
broke up in the air and killed 29 people on the ground 
but with air shows in europe claiming a rising toll including 
an airbus crash in june that killed three people at habsheim 
france demands have grown for a ban on such events 
honley said there are still sensible ways of flying displays 
the red arrows will put on a sensible display 
