<TEXT>
cuba has become one of the most heavily 
militarized countries in the world with more than 250000 
personnel under arms and another 15 million in militia units 
according to us government and independent sources 
by lavishing attention and resources on the military and with a 
substantial assist from the soviet union cuba can send large 
numbers of troops on foreign expeditions without sacrificing its 
ability to defend its own territory 
there are an estimated 60000 cubans serving in angola a figure 
which exceeds by more than 20000 the size of the army of the 
military dictatorship that preceded president fidel castros rise 
to power almost 30 years ago 
state department figures indicate that in latin america only 
brazil with a population 13 times cubas has a comparable 
military establishment 
a recent article in the monthly magazine atlantic said that cuba 
has 250 combat aircraft mostly sovietmade migs compared with 
only 45 for canada a country with 2 times the population and a 
vastly larger land area 
cuba also has about 950 battle tanks some in angola compared 
with canadas 114 the article said all of the equipment is 
delivered for free by the soviet union 
cuba spent an estimated 10 per cent of its government budget on 
the military in 1985 higher than all but a few countries worldwide 
the cuban troop presence in angola has been a sore point for the 
reagan administration which has been trying through diplomatic 
talks to encourage a withdrawal 
the talks have produced agreement on a statement of principles 
by the parties but critics point out there are 40000 more cuban 
troops in angola than when us diplomats undertook their 
initiative more than seven years ago 
in the evolution of the cuban military cuban affairs expert 
rafael fermoselle wrote that cuba has remained in a high state of 
combat readiness since the early 1960s but starting in 1980 
castro has placed the whole country on a wartime footing without 
parallel 
in that year castro began organizing the socalled territorial 
troop militias known by its spanish initials mtt in response to 
his stated concern that ronald reagan a presidential nominee at 
the time posed a threat to the revolution 
by incorporating most ablebodied citizens including women 
into a national defense structure castro felt that no invading 
force could conquer cuba the united states could defeat the cuban 
army but not an entire people according to the theory 
in his atlantic article author john hoyt williams estimated 
that there were 15 million armed and trained men and women in the 
mtts by 1986 arrayed in about 1000 regiments 
japan in the summer of 1945 was not nearly so well prepared to 
resist invasion williams wrote 
an added defense mechanism is the committees for the defense of 
the revolution with a 1986 membership of 66 million the 
committees set up on a blockbyblock basis watch for subversion 
and counterrevolutionary activity 
most troubling to the reagan administration has been cubas 
willingness to deploy military forces abroad angola has been 
cubas most ambitious venture but cubans have been stationed in 
ghana algeria guineabissau ethiopia south yemen syria and 
elsewhere 
in the western hemisphere there are at least several hundred 
cuban military advisers in nicaragua cuba also had a military 
presence in grenada until the 1983 us invasion toppled the 
leftist government there 
a state department report says that cuba has developed an 
extraordinary capacity to influence events in distant lands 
its ability to project power far out of proportion to its size 
is directly related to its association with the soviet union and 
soviet support for the development of its military machine the 
report says 
