<TEXT>
congress returns this week to a full agenda of 
budget and spending bills contra aid welfare reform and antidrug 
legislation but eyeing an early adjournment so lawmakers can 
campaign for reelection 
the house and senate aim to complete work by sept 30 all 435 
house seats and 33 of the 100 senate seats will be up for grabs on 
election day nov 8 
despite the wide assortment of issues congress has to deal with 
the agenda will be chiefly driven by attempts to enact a pentagon 
budget bill and 11 separate spending measures by the oct 1 
beginning of the new fiscal year 
only two of the 13 appropriations bills needed to finance the 
government have been passed and signed into law 
defense will certainly be the big thing that we have to agree 
on im pretty optimistic that everything else can be worked out 
sen pete domenici rnm ranking republican on the senate budget 
committee said last week 
sen david pryor dark agreed 
i think the defense budget will be a large part of the agenda 
all the other issues will fall into place because people want to 
get out for the election he said 
reagan last month vetoed the first pentagon budget bill sent him 
by the democraticcontrolled congress because he objected to arms 
control restrictions and cuts in his proposed star wars budget 
the senate has passed a second defense budget which includes 
the same proposed star wars slashes but none of the arms control 
limitations 
when lawmakers return a housesenate conference committee will 
try to write a compromise bill that reagan might sign one of the 
conferees will be sen dan quayle of indiana the republican vice 
presidential nominee 
the senate version of the defense bill also includes a 
democraticbacked contra aid proposal which the house is likely to 
approve with few changes the current contra aid plan expires sept 
30 but the new plan calls for 27 million in nonlethal aid 
food clothing and shelter and sets up procedures for a 
subsequent vote on releasing 165 million in frozen military 
supplies 
if reagan requests the military aid house speaker jim wright 
dtexas has vowed not to stand in the way of a vote 
the senate is trying to avoid a large catchall spending bill 
last years measure known as a continuing resolution merged all 
13 appropriation bills and was 1057 pages long in his state of 
the union address in january reagan threatened to veto a 
similarsize bill this year 
i think we can avoid a big one this year said domenici 
we may end up with a small one but it wont be anything like 
what happened last december 
the spending fights will be played out against the backdrop of a 
presidential race in which two senators are the major party vice 
presidential candidates sen lloyd bentsen of texas is the 
democratic nominee 
if the republicans try to dream up some vote to try to 
embarrass sen bentsen they have to be aware that whatever they do 
could also catch sen quayle pryor said 
while quayle will be among the conferees on the defense bill 
bentsen is one of the housesenate negotiators nearing agreement on 
a plan changing the way the government helps the nations poor 
the administration expressed reservations last month about the 
way the compromise was shaping up but congressional democrats may 
decide to send reagan the bill and force him to decide whether to 
veto it 
the reform effort centers on a greatly expanded work education 
and training program for welfare recipients the biggest stumbling 
block is a provision requiring some recipients to do community work 
both chambers are also trying to come up with legislation 
designed to halt the flow of illegal drugs the house will begin 
work on its version wednesday with the senate to follow later 
a proposal by house democrats which they hope will win gop 
votes would add up to 2 billion a year to the 39 billion the 
federal government spends anually fighting drugs 
the legislation contains more money for education treatment 
rehabilitation and state and local law enforcement 
the house has also tentatively scheduled a sept 14 vote on a 
bill guaranteeing 10 weeks of unpaid jobprotected leave for new 
parents employed by firms of 50 persons or more the business 
community opposes the bill contending it would make companies 
uncompetitive and the government shouldnt mandate employee 
benefits 
