that they are going to suspend the call for producer levies she 
said 
cocoa prices generally have been falling since early 1984 when 
it became apparent that production during the october 
1983september 1984 crop year would significantly exceed demand 
the surplus has risen each year since then arthur stevenson 
cocoa market analyst with prudentialbache securities inc 
estimated that world cocoa stocks on sept 30 the end of the 
current crop year will stand at 705000 metric tons compared with 
594000 metric tons last year 
stocks are expected to increase to nearly 900000 metric tons 
an alltime high in the upcoming crop year he said a metric ton 
is about 2205 pounds 
that is a massive massive burden overhanging the market 
stevenson said in a telephone interview cocoa consumption 
meanwhile has been going up only very slowly he said 
the surplus has weighed heavily on prices the price for 
nearmonth delivery of cocoa on new yorks coffee sugar amp cocoa 
exchange has fallen from about 2800 a metric ton in early january 
1984 to 1202 on friday 
the drop in cocoa prices has had little impact on chocolatebar 
prices because cocoa is a relatively small ingredient in chocolate 
confections stevenson said candy bar prices also reflect 
manufacturers costs for milk sugar packaging and marketing 
besides stevenson said if people eat one chocolate bar a 
week theyre not going to start eating five chocolate bars a week 
because prices are marginally lower 
yet cocoagrowing countries keep increasing their output hoping 
to make up for lower prices by selling more 
the icco is supposed to help support prices by buying surplus 
cocoa and keeping it off the market in a buffer stock but the 
current icco agreement which began in 1987 and runs through 
september 1990 limits the buffer stock to 250000 metric tons and 
it is already at that level stevenson said 
even if icco members should agree to increase the bufferstock 
limit the organization would still be strapped for cash with which 
to buy the cocoa 
the agreement requires cocoaproducing countries to pay the icco 
a 30 levy on every ton of cocoa they export but the largest 
producers including the ivory coast and brazil have stopped 
paying the levies 
producers owe the icco about 70 million in levies of which at 
least 48 million is owed by the ivory coast analysts said 
the icco secretariat has proposed to do away with the levies a 
suggestion that will be debated at the london meeting but analysts 
say the secretariats proposed alternative selling some of the 
bufferstock cocoa to finance icco operations would only drive 
prices down further and exacerabte the problem 
stevenson said some producer nations have suggested that all 
producers withhold some cocoa from the market to drive up prices 
that idea is not likely to fly he said because it is opposed by 
other producers including no 2 brazil 
the ivory coast is the worlds top cocoa producer last year it 
produced 590000 metric tons of cocoa or 29 percent of the world 
supply 
this past week ivory coast officials reportedly said the icco 
was dying and that unless solutions to the markets dilemmas were 
found it would withdraw from the icco at the end of the current 
agreement 
but analysts saw no easy solutions 
the icco agreement simply cannot circumvent supplydemand 
realties stevenson said the agreement does not have control 
where it is most needed it cannot cut back on production nor can 
it boost consumption 
