<TEXT>
a setback for job seekers was good news for 
investors as a rise in the unemployment rate eased inflation fears 
and sent stock and bond prices sharply higher 
the labor departments report friday of a rise in the civilian 
jobless rate to 56 percent in august stirred the biggest rise in 
the treasury bond and note market since oct 22 a few days after 
the stock market crash 
the higher jobless rate calmed a market that has been worried 
for months that the economy was growing too quickly and might go 
into an inflationary spiral 
its bad news i guess for job searchers but its not 
necessarily bad news for consumers in general said george 
iwanicki an associate economist for kidder peabody amp co 
stock prices leaped and the dow jones average of 30 industrial 
stocks rose 5228 points to 205459 its biggest increase since a 
7468point gain on may 31 
the rise of more than 50 points triggered a restriction on 
member firms use of computers for a form of program trading the 
restrictions were designed to avoid chaotic swings in stock prices 
while the overall treasury market had its biggest rise of 1988 
the treasurys closely watched 30year bond staged its 
secondbiggest rally of the year 
the price of the treasurys 30year bond rose 2590 per 1000 
face amount driving its yield down to 904 from 930 percent late 
thursday the only bigger rally of 1988 was a 2625 price increase 
on jan 15 after the government reported a big drop in the trade 
deficit 
the bond market is highly sensitive to inflation and takes 
weaker growth as good news when bond prices rose investors moved 
to the stock market in search of bargains 
in the long run a slight increase in joblessness could mean 
